SENATE BILL 917
J2 6lr2665
By: Senator Mautz
Introduced and read first time: February 6, 2026
Assigned to: Finance
A BILL ENTITLED
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Health Occupations – Practice of Audiology – Definition
3 FOR the purpose of altering the definition of “practice audiology”, including by clarifying
4 that the ordering and performing of certain scanning and imaging are included as
5 these procedures relate to auditory or vestibular conditions in the human ear; and
6 generally relating to the practice of audiology.
7 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
8 Article – Health Occupations
9 Section 2–101(a) and (b)
10 Annotated Code of Maryland
11 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
12 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
13 Article – Health Occupations
14 Section 2–101(q)
15 Annotated Code of Maryland
16 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
17 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
18 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
19 Article – Health Occupations
20 2–101.
21 (a) In this title the following words have the meanings indicated.
22 (b) “Audiologist” means an individual who practices audiology.
23 (q) (1) “Practice audiology” means to:
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from exist in g l aw . *sb0917*

2 SENATE BILL 917
1 (i) Evaluate, diagnose, manage, and treat auditory or vestibular
2 conditions in the human ear;
3 (ii) Prescribe, order, sell, dispense, or fit hearing aids to an
4 individual for the correction or relief of a condition for which hearing aids are worn;
5 (iii) Prescribe, order, sell, dispense, or externally fit a sound
6 processor to an osseo–integrated device for the correction or relief of a condition for which
7 osseo–integrated devices are worn; and
8 (iv) Prescribe, order, sell, dispense, or externally fit a sound
9 processor to a cochlear implant for the correction or relief of a condition for which cochlear
10 implants are worn.
11 (2) “Practice audiology” includes:
12 (i) The conducting of health screenings RELATED TO AUDITORY
13 OR VESTIBULAR CONDITIONS IN THE HUMAN EAR;
14 (ii) The removal of a foreign body from the external auditory canal
15 that is not impacted to the point it requires anesthesia;
16 (iii) The removal of cerumen from the external auditory canal that is
17 not impacted to the point it requires anesthesia;
18 (iv) The ordering of cultures and bloodwork testing as it relates to
19 the auditory or vestibular conditions in the human ear;
20 (v) The ordering and performing of in–office, nonradiographic
21 scanning or imaging of the external auditory canal AS IT RELATES TO THE AUDITORY OR
22 VESTIBULAR CONDITIONS IN THE HUMAN EAR; and
23 (vi) The ordering of radiographic imaging as it relates to the auditory
24 or vestibular conditions in the human ear.
25 (3) “Practice audiology” does not include:
26 (i) Surgery using an instrument, including a laser, a scalpel, a
27 needle, cautery, a cryoprobe, or a suture, in which human tissue is cut, burned, vaporized,
28 removed, or otherwise permanently altered by mechanical means, laser, ionizing radiation,
29 ultrasound, or other means;
30 (ii) Osseo–integrated device surgery;
31 (iii) Cochlear implant surgery; or

SENATE BILL 917 3
1 (iv) The preparation, operation, or performance of radiographic
2 imaging.
3 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
4 October 1, 2026.

